<font color="#FF0000">AUSTRALIAN SHOWERS &amp; MESS HALL</font><br>
<tt>Sun Aug 17  1:41:31 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Here I am again late to the party.  I guess I am a REMF by most standard definitions.  Only spent one night on a listening post.  Lived in a tent on base for 7 months and a large tin roofed hootch for 5.  Most of my time was occupied running my aerial imagery section out of 2 hot, airless deuce and a halfs or working on court martial cases with occasional entire or sector perimeter officer duty.  Got shot at maybe six times, twice by our own artillery, and LZ English was usually mortared when I was on perimeter officer duty.  Lost a sergeant to a jeep accident and a specialist to Hogkins disease, both medevac'd back home.  Did my job scouring photos, infrared and radar imagery for signs of Charlie.  Successful only once, after one of my hand held aerial photo missions.  The S-2 wanted detailed maps for briefings, and I would produce, once staying up 36 hours straight to get it done right and on time.  It was burnt immediately after the briefing, and I was woke up to fly a mission after only 4 1/2 hours sleep.  I did what I was assigned to do as best as I could.  When short of enlisted men, burnt the used imagery myself in a 55 gal drum, and film burns hotter than shit.  Of course, we had steaks and booze at promotion parties, time for volleyball before supper and poker after and ice cream once or twice a week from a local company in Qui Nhon.  And Chet, you've never tasted anything quite like Vietnamese &quot;coconut ice cream&quot;, the Ba-Mui-Ba of flavors.  Still, the only thing I've always felt a bit uncomfortable about is the Bronze Star I got upon DEROS, despite Maj. O'Kane's &quot;Don't worry about it, you earned it&quot;.  Can't say I've ever worn my ribbons since separation from service; though I've put on the old &quot;Drive-On&quot; rag a few times in recent years for some events.
<p><code>-- gerald_ney@icpphil.navy.mil  (Gerald Ney, &quot;professor&quot;, 7/68-7/69) </code><p>


